Okay so you have a number of problems. As the comments suggest you are not calling the actual mail() function at all currently.

The mail() function takes a number of arguments and can have a number of issues with mail actually getting delivered if not constructed correctly.

This line:

     $mml($_POST[&#39;email&#39;],&#39;Reset Password&#39;,$msg,$headers);

Should be:

     $mnl = mail($_POST[&#39;email&#39;],&#39;Reset Password&#39;,$msg,$headers);

This will mean you will get a boolean of true/false if the FUNCTION succeded. (This does not necessarily mean your mail will get where it needs to go...) To ensure you&#39;re mail is actually going to get where it is intended you need to make sure your headers are all constructed correctly and on top of this that your DNS records are configured correctly (DKIM, SPF etc.)

Consider the following code snippet:
 
        $hostname 		= &quot;yourhostname.org&quot;;
	    $date 			= date(&#39;r&#39;, time());
        $nameto     	= &quot;Mr. Target&quot;;
	    $recipient      = &quot;target@targetdomain.com&quot;;
        $from 			= &quot;origin_address@yourdomain.net&quot;;
	    $namefrom 		= &quot;Mr. Sender&quot;;
    	$subject		= &quot;Password Reset Thingy&quot;;
        
        $headers = [];
		$headers[] = &quot;MIME-Version: 1.0&quot;;
		//	$headers[] = &quot;Content-type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;Content-type: text/html; charset=utf-8&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;From: $namefrom &lt;$from&gt;&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;Sender: $namefrom &lt;$from&gt;&quot;;
		//	$headers[] = &quot;Bcc: Some Other Dude &lt;me@mydomain.net&gt;&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;Reply-To: $namefrom &lt;$from&gt;&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;To: $nameto &lt;$recipient&gt;&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;Subject: $subject&quot;;
		$headers[] = &quot;Message-ID: &lt;&quot;. sha1(microtime(true)) .&quot;@$hostname&gt;&quot;; //This is essential for getting to Gmail addresses.... 
		$headers[] = &quot;X-Mailer: PHP/&quot;.phpversion();
		$headers[] = &quot;Date: $date&quot;;
		$headers = implode(&quot;\r\n&quot;, $headers);

        $mnl = mail($recipient,$subject,$body,$headers,&quot;-f $from&quot;) ;

So including the -f switch in the mail function is important (to force it to send), also the headers need to be constructed in as much detail as possible to avoid getting picked up by spam filters. You will have to read up in your own time about proper header construction it&#39;s beyond the scope of what I am willing to type out here.

